  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is my Miele W1 really 24 inches wide — does that matter for service?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes to both. The W1 series is 24 inches wide — European compact format — not the 27-inch standard on Whirlpool, Samsung, LG, GE, and Maytag. This is why Miele fits stackable closets in Wilshire Corridor condos and butler's pantries in Bel Air where 27-inch laundry won't. For service, the format matters: parts are Miele-specific (a generic 27-inch washer drain pump won't fit), diagnostic protocols are European-standard, and the service technician needs W1-specific training. A 27-inch-oriented laundry tech can diagnose the symptom wrong on a W1. We stock W1 parts on the truck and our techs are trained on the platform."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does F11 on my Miele washer mean?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "F11 is a drainage fault — water cannot exit the drum fast enough. Diagnostic order: remove the kick panel at the front-bottom-left and open the debris filter hatch (lower kick-strip), clear debris (coins, hairpins, small fabric pieces are the usual finds), straighten the drain hose behind the machine. 60% of F11 codes resolve at the filter without parts. If code persists: drain pump impeller is broken or jammed ($285-$385 replacement), or the drain pump motor itself has failed. We carry W1 drain pumps on the truck. LA-specific note: hard-water mineral deposits on the pump impeller accelerate pump wear on 7+ year old W1 units."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "F211, F212, F213, or F214 — what are these TwinDos codes?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "All four codes indicate a short circuit or sensor fault in the TwinDos automatic detergent dosing system. TwinDos uses two flacons (UltraPhase 1 and UltraPhase 2) that dispense through sensor-monitored tubes into the drum. When sensor signals go out of spec, one of these codes posts. Temporary workaround: dose detergent manually via the detergent drawer at the top of the machine while waiting for service. Diagnostic: we test each TwinDos sensor and the tubing for mineral buildup before replacing parts. Sensor replacement $185-$265. On older W1 units, we recommend running TwinDos Care maintenance rinse every 6 months to prevent this from recurring."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "My W1 bangs during spin cycle",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Shock absorber wear. The W1 drum assembly is suspended on four shock absorbers that damp vibration during high-speed spin (up to 1,600 RPM on some W1 models). When absorbers wear out around year 7-10, the drum has too much travel during spin and bangs against the cabinet. Unlike some brands where absorbers are replaced one at a time, Miele specifies replacement as a complete set of four for balanced damping. Set replacement $385-$540. We also check the suspension springs and drum-mounting hardware at the same visit — sometimes what looks like shock wear is actually a broken spring mount that needs its own attention."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much does Miele washer repair cost?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Diagnostic is $89, waived with repair. Typical Miele W1 washer repairs: drain pump $285-$385, water inlet valve $245-$345, shock absorber set (4) $385-$540, door lock $195-$285, door gasket $285-$420, heating element $265-$385, NTC temperature sensor $145-$215, pressure switch $165-$235, TwinDos sensor assembly $185-$265, TwinDos Care maintenance rinse $95 flat, motor carbon brushes (older W1 models) $165-$245, main control board $640-$920, user interface / touch control $385-$560. Labor and parts quoted before work starts."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "My W1 won't unlock the door after cycle ends",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Door lock motor failed, or the drum-water sensor thinks there's still water in the drum (safety interlock). First: check the drain filter — clogged filter leaves residual water that blocks unlock. Clear the filter and wait 60 seconds for safety timer. If that doesn't unlock, the door lock motor has failed ($195-$285 replacement, 40-minute job). Emergency manual release: there's an emergency release pull behind the drain filter hatch — we show you where it is on-site. Don't force the door open; you'll break the latch mechanism and turn a $195 fix into a $385 fix."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
