          <p>Earlier W1 generations 2014-2020. Some models used belt-drive motors (newer units are direct-drive). Parts availability good from Miele USA distribution. 10+ year old W1 units are typically running on original pumps — economics favor repair for any component-level failure.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="footnote">Little Giants commercial W-Series washers (sometimes installed in residential properties as the in-unit laundry for small-format studios or as backup in large estates) — we service residential installs case-by-case. Professional PW Series follows different maintenance schedules than residential W1.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── W1 FAULT CODES ── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">W1 fault codes</p>
      <h2>Reading W1 washer fault codes — decoder table</h2>
      <p>Miele W1 washers display F-codes that map to specific component faults. Code structure matches European standard and is well-documented in Miele USA service materials. Here's the decoder for the most common codes.</p>
      <table class="price-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Code</th><th>Meaning &amp; common cause</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>F1 / F2</strong></td><td>Temperature sensor short-circuited — NTC sensor in the drum circuit failed or wiring harness faulted</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F10</strong></td><td>Water intake blocked — stopcock closed, inlet filter clogged, hose kinked, pressure below spec</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F11</strong></td><td>Drainage fault — drain filter blocked, kinked drain hose, drain pump impeller broken or motor failed</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F15</strong></td><td>Overfill — water level sensor stuck, inlet valve stuck open</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F16</strong></td><td>Excess foam detected — wrong or too much detergent, foam sensor trigger</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F19</strong></td><td>Hot water inlet fault — hot-water supply not detected at correct temperature, hot inlet valve issue</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F24</strong></td><td>Heating element fault — element open, heater relay failed, temp sensor disagreement</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F63</strong></td><td>Oversudsing detected — secondary foam code, often triggered alongside or after F16</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F70</strong></td><td>Waterproof/AquaStop triggered — base pan float switch detected water, full leak protection engaged</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F78 / F79</strong></td><td>Electrical supply fault — frequency or voltage anomaly (shared circuit dimmer interference common in LA)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>F211 / F212 / F213 / F214</strong></td><td>TwinDos sensor short circuit — one of the four dosing-system sensors faulted (UltraPhase 1 or 2 flacon sensor, or tubing sensor)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Drum lamp fault</strong></td><td>Drum interior lamp not fitted correctly or has dislodged — repositioning fix, not electrical</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>"Call Service" notification</strong></td><td>Higher-level technical fault — requires service engineer diagnosis, usually control or communication</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>Reset sequence: press and hold the Start/Stop button for 5 seconds, or turn off at the breaker for 60 seconds. Most transient codes clear with reset. Persistent codes after full reset indicate a real hardware fault and need service. About 45% of W1 codes we see resolve at the filter or reset level without parts; 40% need a single component replacement; 15% need control board work.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── COMMON PROBLEMS ── -->
  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">Common failures</p>
      <h2>The eight things that break on a Miele W1 washer</h2>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>1. Won't drain — F11 flashing, water pooled in drum</h3>
        <p>Drainage fault. Open the drain filter hatch at the front-bottom-left (behind the kick panel), unscrew the filter, clear debris — coins, hairpins, small fabric pieces are the usual finds. 60% of F11 codes resolve at the filter with no parts. If persistent: drain pump impeller broken ($285-$385) or drain pump motor failed. Filter cleanup is free with service visit; pump replacement is a 45-minute job. We carry W1 drain pumps on the truck for single-visit resolution.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>2. F211-F214 — TwinDos dispensing fault</h3>
        <p>Sensor short circuit in the TwinDos system — one of the four dosing sensors (UltraPhase 1 flacon, UltraPhase 2 flacon, or tubing) faulted. Temporary workaround: dose detergent manually via the top drawer. Diagnostic: check flacons are properly seated (pull and reseat, 20% resolve this way), check for detergent clumping in the tubes (run TwinDos Care maintenance rinse, $95 service), test sensors with a meter. Sensor replacement $185-$265. We recommend TwinDos Care rinse every 6 months as preventive maintenance on W1 units that sit unused for more than 2-3 weeks at a time.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>3. Bangs during high-speed spin</h3>
        <p>Shock absorber wear. The W1 drum is suspended on four shock absorbers that damp vibration during spin (1,400-1,600 RPM). When absorbers wear out around year 7-10, drum travel exceeds spec and bangs against the cabinet. Miele specifies replacement as a complete set of four for balanced damping, not one at a time. Set replacement $385-$540, 90-minute job. We also check suspension springs and drum-mounting hardware — sometimes a broken spring mount masquerades as shock wear.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>4. Door won't unlock after cycle ends</h3>
        <p>Safety interlock or door lock motor. First check: drain filter — clogged filter leaves residual water in the drum sensor circuit and blocks unlock for safety. Clear filter, wait 60 seconds for safety timer, door should release. If not: door lock motor has failed ($195-$285, 40-minute replacement). Emergency manual release is behind the drain filter hatch — we show the location on-site. Don't force the door — breaking the latch turns a $195 fix into $385 (latch assembly replacement).</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>5. F16 or F63 — excess foam, cycle interrupted</h3>
        <p>Wrong detergent or over-dosing. Common LA causes: using standard American HE detergent at recommended doses (too much for W1's water-efficient wash), using non-HE detergent (major foam issue), or double-dosing when TwinDos is active and owner adds manual detergent too. Fix: run a rinse cycle without detergent to clear residual foam, switch to Miele UltraPhase or a low-foam HE detergent at reduced dose (W1 needs about 1/3 the dose of a 27-inch American washer). No parts needed. Persistent F16 after detergent correction points to a foam sensor drift — $165 sensor replacement.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>6. F24 — dishes coming out cold, heating element fault</h3>
        <p>Similar to Miele dishwasher F24. Heating element open-circuit (most common on 8+ year old W1 from hard-water scale buildup on the element), heater relay on control board, or NTC temperature sensor disagreeing with the heater state. Heating element tests 20-30 ohms good. Element replacement $265-$385. We descale the new element's mount surface during install to reduce recurrence. LA hard-water W1 units sometimes need element replacement every 7-8 years versus the 12-15 year expected life in softer water markets.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>7. F70 — water detected in base pan (AquaStop)</h3>
        <p>AquaStop leak protection triggered. Root cause is a real leak — degraded door gasket ($285-$420), drain pump housing seal failure (pump replacement), loose hose clamp inside the cabinet, or cracked dispenser housing. We find the leak before resetting AquaStop; otherwise it re-triggers on next cycle. On W1, the base-pan float switch rarely false-triggers, so F70 almost always indicates a real leak that needs physical investigation.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="problem">
        <h3>8. Motor noise, brushes wearing (pre-2020 belt-drive W1 only)</h3>
        <p>Carbon brushes on older belt-drive W1 models wear over years of use and eventually trigger motor stutter or complete motor failure. Symptom: humming without drum rotation, or rotation in starts and stops. Brush replacement $165-$245, 60-minute job. Note: this applies ONLY to older W1 generations (pre-2020, belt-drive). Current direct-drive W1 models don't have carbon brushes — the motor architecture is different and runs maintenance-free for the life of the unit.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── WARRANTY ── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow-sub">Warranty context</p>
      <h2>The W1 warranty structure — and when to call us</h2>
      <p>Miele USA W1 warranty is strong by American standards: 2 years on all parts and labor, <strong>10 years on the motor and drum</strong>. The 10-year motor/drum coverage is why W1 owners shouldn't worry about major mechanical failure through the first decade — those components are covered. During the warranty window, call Miele USA at <strong>1-800-843-7231</strong> for Authorized Service Agent dispatch at no parts cost.</p>
      <p>Post-warranty (units past 2 years) is where we work. The 2021-2023 W1 generation is passing this mark now — the first wave of owners is seeing first service needs in 2025-2026. Typical calls: drain filter cleanup, shock absorber set replacement, TwinDos sensor cleanup, door lock motor replacement. None of these touch the 10-year motor/drum warranty, so owners don't lose warranty standing by using us. Faster response than an Authorized Service dispatch, lower labor rate, same factory training. For in-warranty motor or drum issues, call Miele first — those repairs should be free to you.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

